If any step fails, the chain jumps directly to .No need to clutter your logic with conditionals at every step.Callbacks worked — but Promises made things cleaner, readable, and easier to debug.They also laid the groundwork for , which we’ll cover in another post.But if you’re still using nested callbacks in 2025 — you’re missing out on simpler, more maintainable code.Clean code is not just about how it works.Write async code that reads like syncLet’s be honest. \n Most people don’t understand async/await.They it. \n Theyit. \n But they don’t it.First, what is async/await?Before , we had this:fetchData()
  .then(res => process(res))
  .catch(err => handle(err))
It worked. But chains get messy. \n Now imagine three, four, five async calls in a row.async function run() {
